  <h2>The Call I Get Every Week</h2>

  <p>
    "Hey, I've got a 1987 [something] and the [something] broke and nobody makes it anymore." That's the call. Every week. Sometimes it's a boat part, sometimes it's an automotive trim piece, sometimes it's a clip for a piece of industrial equipment that the manufacturer stopped supporting in 2004.
  </p>

  <p>
    The answer is always the same: send me the broken one. Or send me measurements. Or send me a photo with a ruler next to it for scale. We'll figure it out.
  </p>

  <h2>How Reverse Engineering Actually Works</h2>

  <p>
    There's no magic to this. It's patient, careful measurement and modeling. Here's the typical process:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Get the original:</strong> Even if it's broken, cracked, or worn. A broken part tells you everything — dimensions, mounting points, geometry, where it failed and why.</li>
    <li><strong>Measure everything:</strong> Calipers, micrometers, sometimes a scanner for complex geometry. Every hole, every radius, every wall thickness.</li>
    <li><strong>Model it:</strong> CAD from scratch. I don't just copy the original — I improve it. If it broke because of a thin wall or a sharp corner, the new version fixes that.</li>
    <li><strong>Choose the right material:</strong> The original was probably injection-molded ABS or nylon. The 3D printed version needs to match or exceed those properties. Sometimes that means a different polymer entirely.</li>
    <li><strong>Print, test, iterate:</strong> First print is a fit check. Does it mount? Do the holes line up? Does it clear adjacent parts? Then the final version prints in production material.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Real Examples</h2>

  <p>
    A guy called me about a dashboard vent for a 1990s truck. The original was brittle, cracked into four pieces, and the dealer wanted nothing to do with it. I glued the pieces together, measured the assembly, modeled it in CAD, and printed it in ASA. Took three days. He had a functioning vent that matched the original appearance and snapped into place like factory.
  </p>

  <p>
    A marina contacted me about a water intake strainer housing for a boat engine. The part was 15 years out of production. The only option was a complete housing replacement at $800. I printed the strainer body in PETG-CF for $45 in materials. It's been running for eight months without issue.
  </p>

  <p>
    A collector car owner needed a set of interior door handle escutcheons for a vintage European car. Nobody makes them. I printed prototypes in PLA to verify the fit, then final parts in ASA with a smooth finish. He's showing the car now with parts nobody can tell aren't original.
  </p>

  <h2>Why This Matters</h2>

  <p>
    Planned obsolescence is real. Companies stop making parts because it's more profitable to sell you a new product. Equipment that works perfectly fine gets scrapped because one plastic component failed and there's no replacement.
  </p>

  <p>
    That's wasteful and it's frustrating. 3D printing breaks that cycle. If we can measure it, we can model it. If we can model it, we can print it. The part lives again, the equipment stays in service, and the landfill gets one less perfectly good machine.
  </p>

  <h2>Send Us Your Broken Parts</h2>

  <p>
    Seriously. If you've got something that broke and nobody makes a replacement, <a href="/contact">get in touch</a>. Ship us the broken part or send detailed photos and measurements. We'll tell you honestly whether we can replicate it, what material makes sense, and what it'll cost. Most of the time the answer is yes, and the cost is a fraction of what you'd pay for an OEM replacement — if you could even find one.
  </p>
